Congressman Comer was sworn in to the 115th Congress today. Pictured is his voting card and his Congressional license plate with his seniority rank. Due to his being sworn in immediately following the November election due to former Congressman Whitfield's resignation, Congressman Comer has already moved up 51 spots in seniority after only 6 weeks of service!

Congressman Comer voted tonight for HR 21 (The Midnight Rules Relief Act) which will prevent President Obama from passing more unnecessary regulations before he leaves office. The regulatory burden that the Obama Administration has placed on our small businesses is one of the biggest issues holding our economy back and preventing Americans from getting good paying jobs.

Congressman Comer congratulates one of his best friends in the world -- Jeff Hoover R-Jamestown --upon his election as Speaker of the Kentucky House of Representatives in Frankfort this week. He is pictured here taking the oath of office by former Kentucky Senate President and current Judge David Williams. Both Hoover and Williams are Comer's constituents, friends, advisors, and close personal friends.

Last night Congressman Comer was proud to vote for the REINS Act, which passed the House. It would require Congress to approve all new major regulations  and prevent unelected bureaucrats from holding our economy back.
The Comer kids have taken over Congressman Comer's DC office.  Call Harlan if you need information on legislation or Aniston to request a tour.  They have it all under control!

Congressman Comer gave the Washington Post all access to him for three entire days last week during his recess while he traveled around the district meeting with constituents and hosting town halls. The post chose Congressman Comer because he was one of only 12 Congressmen who hosted a town hall event that week, and the only Congressman who hosted more than one. The Washington Post is the most recognizable political newspaper in America. Their reporter was very professional, spent three full days meeting real people throughout KY-1, and did several fact checks with Congressman Comer before the story was published. It was very refreshing for the Congressman to see a credible reporter with a real newspaper write an accurate account of President Trump's status among the people in KY-1. Below is the feature story in the Sunday Washington Post about Congressman Comer: https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/a-gop-congressman-from-kentucky-wonders-is-this-trump-thing-sustainable/2017/05/20/1cbd5374-3c16-11e7-9e48-c4f199710b69_story.html?utm_term=.6bd95ea39767

Congressman Comer interviewed with CNN this morning to discuss healthcare. He explained his goal of helping to lower private health insurance premiums for working class Americans through offering consumers more options and the freedom to decide on their own unique health insurance plan, taking Medicaid decision making away from Washington and giving states the authority to mange their Medicaid programs, and allowing Kentucky to apply for a federal waiver to put work requirements on able bodied Kentuckians receiving Medicaid benefits. Congressman Comer also reiterated his support for Medicaid as it was originally intended -- to be a temporary safety net for the truly disabled, children living in poverty, people who lost their job until they found a new one, and low income mothers.
